posts.name: oriya
posts.cooked: Hello everyone, we were wondering which CANBUS problems your team had during the season?

posts.name: Yishai Levy
posts.cooked: Using the molex connector on the KrakenX60 PowerPole adapter was horrible for CANBus (at least, without gold molex). More info here

link_counts.title: Announcing Kraken X60 powered by Talon FX!

posts.cooked:
Make sure to secure your CANbus wires!

We had one rip out of a wago when it got caught in a swerve module. Also, Molex greater than Wago when done properly.

Also with Molex, make sure you keep a standard, each device needs a female and a male connector.

CANivore is good, use it if you can!

posts.name: Ryan Radtke
posts.cooked: We had many problems with wagos this year and will be soldering next year(on our swerve modules)

posts.name: H
posts.cooked:
We use a non-standard (if somewhat common) bus architecture. We had issues this year with incorrect topology and termination.

2 main problems were: Stubs that branch in to other stubs, rather than each branching from main bus, and Terminating on each stub rather than once at the end of the main bus.

We‚Äôve also seen issues in the past with inadvertent incorrect termination (left on on PDH , or turned off at the final CAN node) as well as loose connectors flopping around and shorting under acceleration.

posts.name: Chadfrom7226
posts.cooked:
Only had 1 CAN issue this year (thankfully)

A CAN wire got pinched and shorted high and low together sometimes. This only happened after a quick reassembly of a part

We used PWM + Vex PWM Clips

posts.name: Mr. Siefen | 453
posts.cooked:
Isolate your wires when soldering. A newer student soldered the can, but didn‚Äôt heat shrink each wire individually. They heatshrunk the outside so the wire looked perfectly fine, but the solder joints were contacting each other and taking the whole bus down.

It wasn‚Äôt until we started to dissect each connection and take the shrink tubing off we figured it out.

posts.name: Tom
posts.cooked: I am very proud of it, but this year, 0 CAN problems everything worked straight away, that is a big difference to last year where we had a lot of can problems

posts.name: Calvin Hou
posts.cooked: We actually had the exact opposite. Absolutely zero can issues all season with wago 221 inline connectors both on our canivoire bus and the rio bus. Wagos need to be properly secured and all connections going into a wago needs to be properly crimped with a ferrule. Everything needs to be tug-tested once installed with a proper amount of strain relief. We like wagos because of their modularity, we can swap out a whole spare module on our bot without cutting or splicing, just a direct swap.

posts.name: Yishai Levy
posts.cooked: Adding another one I had right now If your CANBus shows problems only when the robot is enabled, one of your motors has a short to the frame in a very unexpected way (for us it was a kraken that sends voltage down its axle when it‚Äôs enabled, which made it harder to detect)
